What about touch ? Some might answer ready player one. 
But what about smell? Taste? Sense of balance and shift in gravity?
More importantly, what about what we simply don‚Äôt know about the human experience? 
I‚Äôm concerned that as this technology gets more and more compelling and widely available, we might forget, slowly, the complexity of the physical experience.

text_Original:
Wow... this is so incredible...

Photorealistic 3D chats in VR. In VR!!

And again: This looks like a 3D world in VR goggles.
The people have a virtual three-dimensional body that you see in the goggles.
And it doesn't seem to feel like the uncanny valley. It seems natural.

Little conspiracy theory (must be):
Maybe these scans can be replaced with scans from other people? Then some voice imitation...
And now you don't believe anything anymore...
This technology will certainly develop much further.

TicTocVR with completely photorealistic surrogate avatars. No more filtering necessary, just replace the avatar...

The sex and porn industry is probably already in the starting blocks, rubbing its hands. This industry has always been a driver of technology.

At some point it will be so cheap to use this type of technology that it will open up commercial opportunities that we have never seen before...

text_Original: Very, very interesting. So, the photorealism is at a level now that's really satisfying. If I have any kind of a niggle, it would be with the mouth movement when speaking. It looks just a touch too stiff. Perhaps tuning the lip movement to be a little more expressive would take care of that. All in all, this is nothing short of amazing. The possibilities for abuse are also huge, though, as once your facial expressions have been scanned in, anyone who gets access to that data can create deep fakes of you very easily.
